# /etc/usage-dashboard-gui.env  —  root-owned, chmod 600
# Copied here by deploy/pi/install.sh; edit in the two required values.

# Where the server lives and the shared bearer token (same `api-key` the
# server's k8s Secret uses).
SERVER_URL=http://CHANGE-ME:8080
API_KEY=CHANGE-ME

# --- optional ---------------------------------------------------------------

# Frames per second for the GUI render loop (default 10).
# GUI_FPS=10

# Status overlay: tap the status ("Updated…") line for a card with unit
# diagnostics (hostname/IPs, server, running commit, updater health) on the left
# and brightness -/+ on the right. Updater health comes from status files
# update.sh writes under ~/.local/state/usage-dashboard/ — no config needed.
# BRIGHTNESS_STEPS sets how many -/+ notches span dim->full (default 10; try 9/11).
# The chosen level survives sleep/wake and is persisted across reboot to
# ~/.local/state/usage-dashboard/brightness; BRIGHTNESS_STATE_FILE relocates it
# (set empty to remember within the session only).
# BRIGHTNESS_STEPS=10
# BRIGHTNESS_STATE_FILE=

# Backlight sleep schedule. Off by default. Set to 1 to blank the panel on the
# fleet schedule (nightly 00:00-08:00 + weekend Fri 18:00 -> Mon 08:00); a tap
# wakes it until the next sleep boundary (the current window's end or the next
# midnight, whichever is sooner). Off uses `brightness` (0 = fully dark on the
# Touch Display 2), which the GUI user's `video` group can write without sudo.
# Confirm on the unit with (no sudo needed):
#   echo 0 > /sys/class/backlight/*/brightness   # dark; restore with e.g. 15
# BACKLIGHT_SLEEP=1

# Unit identity, used to fetch this unit's schedule from the server (the key in
# the usage-dashboard-schedules ConfigMap). Falls back to the ConfigMap's
# `default` entry when unset/unknown. Set per unit, e.g. mpmusage01.
# UNIT_ID=mpmusage01

# Local schedule override / fallback, used when BACKLIGHT_SLEEP=1 and the server
# returns no schedule (no ConfigMap, or unreachable). Same grammar as the
# ConfigMap values; if unset the built-in fleet default is used.
# BACKLIGHT_SCHEDULE=daily 00:00-08:00; fri 18:00-mon 08:00

# Git ref the auto-updater tracks. Default "main". Pin to a tag
# (e.g. v0.2.0) to freeze a whole fleet on a known-good release.
# UPDATE_REF=main

# Opt-in: also self-redeploy the installer-managed components (the updater
# script, systemd units, X launcher, touch workaround) from the pulled checkout,
# so infra changes reach the unit without a manual install.sh re-run. Off by
# default. Content-addressed + atomic + unit-verify + GUI rollback; lets a push
# to UPDATE_REF change root-owned units, so pair with a pinned ref if that
# matters. See deploy/pi/README.md §6. (Existing units need one install.sh re-run
# to gain the helper before this can take effect.)
# AUTO_REDEPLOY=1
